WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.875
Introducing The Talkboy Ultra! An AI Powered Voice Cloning Toy

00:00:06.375 --> 00:00:09.171
Published on June 14, 2023.

00:00:10.171 --> 00:00:19.202
Note: This blog post is based on a YouTube video I made, which you can watch in the embed, but it also has some stuff that’s not in the video, so read the stuff I wrote below!

00:00:20.202 --> 00:00:29.952
So while I was learning about AI voice cloning technology to make myself sing better (and to make Kanye sing stupid songs), I got an idea into my head that I couldn’t let go of.

00:00:30.452 --> 00:00:42.599
I was reminicing about the original Talkboy Deluxe from the movie Home Alone 2 (and the subsequent commercial that played on kids tv for years after), and how it was supposed to change your voice but really it just kinda slowed it down.

00:00:43.099 --> 00:00:48.454
I realized that I could make the dream of the Talkboy come true, and do it with real life hardware.

00:00:49.454 --> 00:00:54.408
So here’s the story of how I made the Talkboy Ultra, which it turns out is a pretty fun toy.

00:00:55.408 --> 00:00:56.687
Building The Dream

00:00:58.187 --> 00:01:02.582
I knew that I wanted the Talkboy to be a real device, not just some app on a phone.

00:01:03.082 --> 00:01:07.557
Phone apps are cool, but there’s just something about single-purpose devices that hit different.

00:01:08.057 --> 00:01:13.091
They’re more fun and there’s something about pressing a button that’s designed just for a single purpose.

00:01:14.091 --> 00:01:22.163
I was hoping that I could run everything locally on a device, but the voice AI inference requires too much memory, so I went with a client-server approach.

00:01:22.663 --> 00:01:29.056
I started with a Raspberry Pi Zero W as the base, and added a USB audio card with input and output.

00:01:30.056 --> 00:01:33.732
I connected a lavalier microphone and tested recording and playback.

00:01:34.232 --> 00:01:40.065
The recording worked fine but when I plugged in an unamplified speaker, the audio was way too quiet.

00:01:40.565 --> 00:01:46.559
I decided that instead of figuring out how to amplify an audio signal, I would just go with a USB powered speaker.

00:01:47.559 --> 00:01:52.913
With this setup, I could successfully record and playback my voice (after writing some Python code to do that).

00:01:53.913 --> 00:01:58.787
From this foundation, I added a few push buttons for the recording and playback controls.

00:01:59.287 --> 00:02:13.513
I also wanted the device to work without having to plug it in to a power source (for portability) so I added a 1000 mAh Lithium-ion battery pack and a TP4056 Charging Module with micro usb input to charge the battery.

00:02:14.013 --> 00:02:25.202
I also added a MT3608 DC-DC Step Up Boost Power Converter so I could power the Raspberry Pi with it (since the voltage coming out of the battery is 3.7v).

00:02:26.202 --> 00:02:33.714
Finally, I added a 1602 LCD display to show the state of the device, either the currently selected voice or the processing state.

00:02:34.214 --> 00:02:38.529
And to be able to control the power supply to the toy, I added an on/off switch.

00:02:39.029 --> 00:02:43.104
I soldered the components together and amazingly they worked the first time!

00:02:44.104 --> 00:02:51.616
I couldn’t just let the device sit in the cardboard box that I was using for prototyping, so I also designed and 3D printed a case for it.

00:02:52.116 --> 00:03:00.188
I started with a blocky box just to test how the components like the buttons could fit in the holes, then I refined the case to have some smooth, rounded edges.

00:03:00.688 --> 00:03:07.241
I also added a microphone enclosure thing and a handle so I could hold it with one hand, just like the original!

00:03:08.241 --> 00:03:12.396
I used TinkerCad for this, which works pretty well once you learn the controls.

00:03:13.396 --> 00:03:14.515
Software

00:03:16.015 --> 00:03:19.691
Of course, I worked on some software in order to make the toy actually do stuff.

00:03:20.191 --> 00:03:26.024
I wrote everything in Python since it’s pretty portable and runs well on both my laptop and my Raspberry Pi.

00:03:27.024 --> 00:03:33.257
On the Raspberry Pi, I wrote some code to handle button presses for recording, playback and voice selection.

00:03:33.757 --> 00:03:38.952
I also had to write some code to make HTTP requests between the Raspberry Pi and my laptop (web server).

00:03:39.952 --> 00:03:46.665
The basic workflow is: I press and hold the record button, and say whatever it is I want to hear in a different voice.

00:03:47.165 --> 00:03:54.357
When I release the button, the recording stops and the Talkboy sends the audio file to my web server along with the voice model to use.

00:03:54.857 --> 00:03:58.613
The LCD switches from the currently selected voice to “Processing….”

00:03:59.113 --> 00:04:05.985
The web server receives the audio file and runs the inference on it, then sends the response with the changed voice file back to the Talkboy.

00:04:06.485 --> 00:04:10.561
The LCD switches back to the voice display to show that it’s done processing.

00:04:11.061 --> 00:04:15.376
Then when I hit the green button again I can hear the changed voice.

00:04:16.376 --> 00:04:24.128
I already had some voice models and the script to infer audio from one voice to another set up since I used it in my previous project on AI voice cloning.

00:04:24.628 --> 00:04:33.258
I just had to write a simple Flask web server to respond to the HTTP requests, run the inference script, and then send the file back to the Talkboy (so simple).

00:04:34.258 --> 00:04:47.605
The delay between finishing the recording and being ready to play back the voice depends on how long the recording is. I would say that the total latency is probably around 5-15 seconds for a typical short recording, which isn’t too bad.

00:04:48.105 --> 00:04:58.175
I could probably optimize the speed by streaming audio to and from the web server but that’s more complicated and I’m not really willing to do that just for a stupid gag project like this.

